What a wonderful place!
The food is super, the entertainment decidedly hokey, and the beer... Oh the beer.
I'm a beer-lover and was very happy with, not only the quality, but also the sizes available -- pints!
There were songs about beer (sung in German), grown men asking to be paddled on the ass by the waitresses in front of the entire hall, games to win glass steins.
Oh yes, the entire place was up on the tables dancing and singing along as best (or worst) as they could.
Hofbrauhaus isn't your typical "sit-down" restaurant by any means.
Rather, the eating "hall" is full of tables that are shared among everyone.
Groups are seated far enough apart to have their own space, but I can see the place being filled & mingled with patrons on a busy night.
This time around, I took some advice from a fellow Yelper and ordered the stuffed chicken (Grillhendl).
It's difficult to describe, but the flavor was definitely German and very delicious.
Erin Ashley (my wonderful woman) ordered some type of salad -- potato salad mixed with green salad & a type of schnitzel on top.
Oh the glory.
For an appetizer we were served a soft preztel accompanied with three sauces -- spicy mustard, sweet-spicy mustard, and a thick-creamy spread made from Brie cheese.
Personally, I'm not a big fan of Brie.
But this spread is to live for.
I sang.
I danced.
I drank.
I didn't win a stein, but I will keep going back to have fun and play the game.
And so should you.

I've read through a bunch of the reviews and I see common themes for folks disappointed with their experience at the Hofbrauhaus.
Beer Prices 2.
Food price/authenticity 3.
The Band (Music Selection and volume) 4.
Service   First off, I lived in Germany for 5 years and have been to Munich's Oktoberfest several times so I have some perspective to compare fairly.
Beer Price: 15 dollars for a LITER of Beer.
Let's break it down.
A liter of beer is 33.8 ounces.
That is two ounces short of THREE 12 Oz.
BOTTLES.
So I challenge anyone to find real german imported beer on the strip for less than 5 dollars.
If you ask me, you are getting a bargain especially when they are offering their tasty seasonal beers.
Food Prices/Authenticity: Prices may be a bit pricey when you are used to Sunday dinner with the family at Chili's or the Cracker Barrel.
This restaurant is a destination in itself.
The servings are large and the food is cooked by actual German chefs.
It may not be EXACTLY to the taste of what you'd find in Germany, but it's pretty close.
A steak in Germany doesn't quite taste like an American Porterhouse either.
I've seen the servers explain the menu choices to folks who are unfamiliar.
The Band: It is loud in the main hall in the evenings.
If you want it to be a bit quieter, ask for the beer garden.
The band plays a mix of german music and american classics.
Just like the Hofbrau tent at Oktoberfest in Munich.
The Germans LOVE to sing John Denver's "Country Roads" and Neil Diamond's "Sweet Caroline" so if you think you are getting Las Vegas cheesiness, you aren't.
You are getting authentic German cheesiness.
Service: The servers I've dealt with all know their beers and the menu.
They can explain the food before you order and get disappointed by not getting what you wanted.
They can also recommend some of the more popular dishes as well.
These servers (as well as many others in Vegas) also deal with a very large amount of foreign tourists who either don't understand that they depend on gratuities (unlike in Europe) or they feign ignorance.
I would go crazy having to work in that beer hall with all that noise and all the demanding customers while trying to keep a smile on my face.
If you can't afford to tip correctly (at any restaurant) then maybe you need to lower your price point for food and entertainment.
The Hofbrauhaus is not a carbon copy of the Oktoberfest in Munich, but it is the closest thing to actually being there.
Arrive there in a mood to eat, drink, and sing with your table mates and you'll leave with an unforgettable memory of Oktoberfest in the desert.

My wife and I had a great time!
We walked over from the hard rock for lunch and spent a few hours eating, drinking and singing.
The food is traditional german with sausage, kraut, hot potato salad, schnitzel, etc.
Good bears and some really good deserts!
We will return!

